          "text": "Leo, adopting a third party looks cheaper, but it is mostly false economy. No existing integration matches the required combination: local execution, source-adjacent baselines, correct approval semantics, and Storybook-native review.\n\n## Ecosystem state\n\n| Option | Pros | Blocking cons | Verdict |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| [Chromatic addon](https://github.com/chromaui/addon-visual-tests) | Best Storybook UX: panel, toolbar, sidebar statuses, review workflow | Thin client over Chromatic’s private GraphQL/capture/review backend; cannot become local by changing storage | UX reference only |\n| [storybook-visual-regression](https://github.com/mjbeswick/storybook-visual-regression) | Local Playwright runs inside Storybook | Storybook 8-era; overcomplicated transports; approval performs a fresh capture instead of approving the reviewed image | Do not adopt |\n| [Creevey](https://github.com/creevey/creevey) | Best artifact and approval model; promotes the exact reviewed candidate; capable comparison UI | Separate application, not native Storybook UX; title-derived paths; internal Storybook dependencies | Borrow semantics |\n| [storybook-addon-playwright](https://github.com/ccpu/storybook-addon-playwright) | Source-adjacent `__screenshots__`; Playwright readiness logic; args/globals support | Large Storybook 8 package with unrelated recorder/editor features and weak filesystem confinement | Borrow storage patterns |\n| [Loki](https://github.com/oblador/loki) | Mature Storybook capture and reproducible Docker workflow | Aging integration model; CLI/filesystem review rather than Storybook-native management | Engine reference |\n| [Lost Pixel](https://github.com/lost-pixel/lost-pixel) | Good Storybook discovery, capture stabilization, masks and breakpoints | Archived/sunset; hosted product owned the review UX | Engine reference only |\n| [reg-suit](https://github.com/reg-viz/reg-suit) | Clean expected/actual/diff pipeline and useful result states | Generic CLI/reporting system, not Storybook-first | Borrow result taxonomy |\n| Raw [Playwright](https://playwright.dev/docs/api/class-page#page-screenshot) | Stable capture primitives: animation suppression, masks, CSS scale, PNG output | No Storybook status, storage, comparison, approval, or review workflow | Use as foundation |\n\n## Recommendation\n\nBuild ours. Confidence: high.\n\nBut “build ours” should mean a focused integration package, not a new visual-testing framework:\n\n- Storybook manager panel, toolbar, test-provider and sidebar status integration.\n- Playwright for capture.\n- Small PNG comparison dependency.\n- Storybook index `importPath` for locating each story file.\n- Committed source-adjacent baselines.\n- Gitignored candidate and diff artifacts.\n- Exact-candidate approval: promote the image the user reviewed, never recapture during approval.\n- Same runner and result schema for Storybook and CI.\n- One same-origin typed manager-to-Node protocol.\n\nDo not build:\n\n- Chromatic-compatible GraphQL.\n- Authentication, cloud uploads, sharing or branch baseline graphs.\n- A second standalone review application.\n- Action recording.\n- Elaborate comparison UI initially.\n- Multi-browser capture until Chromium behavior is stable.\n\n## Why not adopt and patch?\n\nAny plausible adoption leaves us replacing its core:\n\n- Chromatic: replace the entire backend.\n- Creevey: replace the entire Storybook integration and storage identity.\n- `storybook-visual-regression`: replace transport, approval semantics and status integration.\n- Addon Playwright: remove most of the package and migrate its Storybook internals.\n\nThat is a fork with inherited constraints, not leverage. A new package borrowing proven patterns will be smaller and easier to extract later.\n\n## Current repo state\n\nResearch only; no implementation yet. The repo has 38 story files, roughly 200 stories, and no baseline infrastructure. The evidence-backed report is here:\n\n[Prior-art research report](/home/leon0399/Projects/llame/docs/research/2026-07-20-storybook-local-visual-testing-prior-art/README.md)\n\nRealistic scope: roughly one engineering week for a defensible Chromium-first integration; additional time for hardened CI portability and polished comparison controls. Confidence: moderate.",
